RlnOfActyToAccomOfExmptPrpsGrp.RelationshipStatementTxt: Annenberg Learner advances excellent teaching in American schools by creating and distributing multimedia educational resources for teachers and students and by communicating best teaching practices to educators, administrators, and the public. Annenberg Learner contracts with award-winning multimedia producers who work with academic and professional development experts in each discipline to create video, print, and web resources. Annenberg Learner provides free access to digital formats through its website: www.learner.org and also distributes DVD and telecourse licenses for these materials to encourage the development of more effective ways to share ideas and knowledge.

The Annenberg Space for Photography and Skylight Studios are dedicated to exhibiting compelling photography and to providing multi-media content that complements and extends the Photography Space exhibits. Events include lectures and Meet & Greets, often featuring well-known and up and coming photographers. Admission to both spaces is free. As part of the educational experience, guests to the spaces can purchase photography books and postcards as well as other items related to the exhibits. Hands on educational events and workshops are periodically offered for a nominal fee. The Annenberg Foundation's Explore Annenberg LLC teamed up with Facebook to participate in the Facebook Live beta program. With the program, Explore Annenberg LLC broadcasted Live Cam Footage into the Explore, Dog Bless You, and related facebook pages to share content from live cameras positioned on animals and unique places around the world.

GeneralExplanationGrp.MediumExplanationTxt: Form 990-PF, Part IX-A Line 1: The Annenberg Space for Photography/Skylight Studios (Los Angeles, CA) The Annenberg Space for Photography is a cultural destination dedicated to exhibiting compelling photography. It is the first solely photographic cultural destination in Los Angeles. Annenberg Space for Photography conveys a range of human experiences and serves as an expression of the philanthropic work of the Annenberg Foundation and its Directors. The intimate environment features state-of-the-art, high- definition digital technology as well as traditional and digital prints by some of the worlds most renowned and emerging photographers. The exhibits change multiple times per year to attract new audiences; and, the common thread throughout is one of rich emotion. The Photography Space informs and inspires the public by connecting photographers, philanthropy and the human experience through powerful imagery and stories. Admission is free. In addition, The Annenberg Foundation has a second location called Skylight Studios that serves as an extension of The Photography Space. Skylight Studios serves as the venue for multi-media content and events, including lectures, installations that are extensions of the Photography Spaces exhibits, Meet & Greets and workshops. These deepen the connection and accessibility between photographers and public guests. The Annenberg Foundation also hosts special events such as Summer Concerts where admission is free. www.annenbergspaceforphotography.org Fiscal Year 2016 (January 1, 2016 December 31, 2016) Photography Space - Public Walk-In Attendance at the Photography Space: 47,588 - Attendance at Opening-Week Events & Special Events: 16,334 (866 Exhibit Opening Events and Special Events; 15,468 Sound in Focus Summer Concert Series) - Number of Exhibits: 3 LIFE: A Journey Through Time (10/24/15-3/20/16), REFUGEE (4/23/16-8/21/16), IDENTITY: Timothy Greenfield-Sanders The List Portraits (9/24/16-2/26/17) - Number of Weekly Thursday Night Lectures: 33 - Number of People Attending Lectures: 3,839 (average of 116 people per lecture) - Number of Public Programming and Workshop Events: 19 - Public Programming Attendance: 2,646 Skylight Studios - Public Walk-In Attendance at Skylight Studios: 16,318 - Number of Exhibits: 3 Pearls of the Planet (10/25/15-3/20/16), New Americans (4/23/16-8/21/16), #girlgaze: a frame of mind (10/22/16-2/26/17) Since Opening March 27, 2009 to December 31, 2016 (Photography Space and Skylight Studios): - Public Walk-In Attendance: 582,333 - Attendance at Opening-Week Events: 22,880 - Number of Exhibits: 19 Exhibits: 1. Form 990-PF, Part IX-A Line 2: Explore Annenberg LLC (Los Angeles, CA) Explore Annenberg LLC (Explore) is a philanthropic multimedia project of the Annenberg Foundation whose mission is to champion the selfless acts of others, create a portal into the soul of humanity and inspire lifelong learning. Explore showcases the selfless acts of individuals and non-profit organizations around the world through documentaries, short films, photographs, live cams, web content and social media. Explore uses the explore.org portal as well as non-profit partner sites, online distribution, such as Facebook Live, YouTube and Ustream, educational programming accessible on cable and satellite television, schools, and social media such as Facebook, Instagram, Tumblr and Twitter, as platforms to reach an audience to connect people, ideas, communities and cultures. In 2016, $6,403,000 in grant support was approved to 38 non-profit organizations. The grantees were identified during fact-finding missions, site visits, meetings, and specials projects. Several projects are highlighted below: - Long Beach Opera, to support the opera Fallujah, a production based on the life of United States Marine Corps Sergeant Christian Ellis, performed at the Long Beach Opera. Grant: $297,100 in 2015 and $75K in 2016. - African Wildlife Foundation, to provide support for the expansion of the Rwanda Volcanoes National Park's gorilla habitat. Grant: $500,000 - Best Buddies, to provide support over three years to support the International Global Expansion Project of Best Buddies International, which will strengthen and expand programming to further enhance the lives of individuals with intellectual disabilities. Grant: $1,275,000 - East Coast Assistance Dogs, to support the organization's mission to enable people with disabilities to gain greater independence and mobility through the use of specially educated dogs. Grant: $500,000 - Service Dog Project, to support the organization's mission to train Great Danes for people with balance and mobility limitations, with priority being given to veterans and their families. Grant: $300,000 of support during 2015 and 2016. - Mpala Research trust, to provide support over two years to support the Mpala Live! project of the Mpala Research Centre, which streams live video of the sights and sounds of an African watering hole. Mpala Live! focuses on a bend in the Ewaso N'giro River in central Kenya, Africa, and documents its resident pod of 26 hippos and other animals including elephants, lions, hyenas, zebras, giraffes, and wild dogs. Grant: $250,000 Dog Bless You The Dog Bless You community grew to over 2 million people in 2016, expanding the reach of the project by over a million Facebook fans. DBY highlights the value of the human and animal bond as a resource for companionship and psychological support. DBY encourages individuals on Facebook to create awareness and grow the community. Explore views the DBY community as an ongoing asset for philanthropic giving. In 2016 DBY continued to grow our network of community leaders and moderators. The Dog Bless You community has continued to watch and promote Explores Dog Live Cams. During 2016, Explore maintained partnerships with Service Dog Project, East Coast Assistance Dogs, Bergin University of Canine Studies, Animal Wellness Centers and Warrior Canine Connection through the Explore Live Cams, which drives traffic to explore.org. Live Cams (Pearls of the Planet) In 2016, Explore continued to grow the live cam mission to bring people closer to nature using live cameras located in places and on animals around the world. Dubbed Pearls of the Planet, the initiative continues to be a vehicle for philanthropic giving, NGO partnerships and widespread inspiration. Explore continues to position its live cam network as a global media brand - in 2016, live cams viewership has exceeded 80 million page views with an average session lasting over 50 minutes, this represents millions of hours of content watched by people around the world. By the end of 2016, Explore hosted or featured 111 live cams. Explore hosted over 200 live chats with our non-profit partners, including Katmai National Park and Preserve, Audubon Society, and Polar Bears International, and National Park Service, offering our global audience the opportunity to interact with non-profit leaders and experts in the field. Explore has continued the partnership with New Earth, a Los Angeles-based nonprofit that works with young adults, in a collaborative effort to give kids recently out of the juvenile justice system real jobs and marketable skills. New Earth works with young men and women from 15 detention centers in Southern California during and after incarceration. For teens with a history of incarceration, finding employment - especially jobs that lead to successful careers - proves to be an insurmountable challenge. Many fall into unemployment, poverty, and crime. Working with Explore, New Earth has employed more than 30 camera operators that assist on the explore webcams, giving them technical training, communication skills, and teaching them film editing, production and multimedia skills. More than a million people watch the feeds online every month to get a glimpse of the most remote regions of the world, but few know that behind a percentage of those cameras are formerly incarcerated juveniles in Los Angeles. To provide viewers with tools for capturing moments on the cams and enhancing user experiences, explore.org developed and implemented snapshot functionality. Viewers took more than 2.5 million photos, some of which are being used by scientists to unlock secrets of species and expand upon a body of data previously unavailable. In some cases, viewers have contributed to science by noting unusual wildlife behavior (such as a brown bear adopting an orphaned cub) or alerted authorities to suspicious activity at the National Parks. Teachers have used the cams to interest inner city kids in nature, to help autistic children focus, and to educate underprivileged children about nature that they would not otherwise experience. Explore provides citizen science surveys for the audubon bird cams to assist with research. In 2016, Explore continued to support Polar Bears Internationals mission to create awareness about global warming by showing how temperature affects the polar bear migration from the Hudson Bay until they depart to their icy hunting grounds. Explore featured and supported the Brown Bear Cams in 2016 through the ongoing partnership with Katmai National Park and Preserve in Alaska. The Brown Bear Cams capture over a hundred Brown Bears that descend on a mile long stretch of Brooks River to feast on the largest Sockeye Salmon run in the world. The Brown Bear cams have continued to inspire a dedicated community of faithful viewers at explore.org/bears. Facebook Partnership In spring 2016 Explore partnered with Facebook to roll out their new Facebook Live feature. Since then our team publishes broadcasts from Explore's live cams to our explore, Dog Bless You, and Cat Bless You Facebook pages at least 15 times daily. Press & Distribution As part of Explores continuing mission to communicate with the public and spread the message of its mission to as many people as possible, Explore further increased its press and distribution during 2016. Explore continued its mission of providing inspirational content to people everywhere including thousands of placements from numerous stories in partnership with the Associated Press, New York Times, Reuters, Mother Nature Network, CCTV, and AFP, USA Today, BuzzFeed, ABC, CNN, CBC, and BBC. Additionally, Explore provided commercial free content to hundreds of newspapers, websites and radio stations. Coverage spanned the globe, with explore.org generating media coverage and traffic from over 30 countries including Japan, India, UAE, Germany, China, Brazil, the European Union and more. In 2016, Explore launched a new email initiative called the Daily Dose of Love, which goes out 5 times per week to almost 60,000 subscribers. Additionally, by the end of the year, Explore had 196,775 registered users on Explore.org. In 2016 Explore continued to cultivate our existing highly engaged communities on social channels and on explore.org. This is demonstrated by the increase of traffic on explore.org, the increased amount of time people spend on the website, mobile and Apple TV aps and the conversations and interactions people are having online regarding Explores content. Explore utilizes the power of social media by activating and inspiring communities on Facebook, Twitter, Instagram, Pinterest and Tumblr. Across our accounts on social networks, explore.org content has generated millions of impressions.

Form 990-PF, Part IX-A Line 3: Metabolic Studio LLC (Los Angeles, CA) In 2016 the Metabolic Studio awarded a total of $4,806,306 in grants to 88 unique non-profit organizations. Of that amount, $1,025,563 was given to the arts, $1,210,000 was given to civic and community, $592,500 was given to health and human services, $1,928,243 was given to animal services and environment, and $50,000 was given to education and youth development. The Metabolic Studio, a direct charitable activity of the Annenberg Foundation, is an organization focused on paradigm shifts, producing devices of wonder to create the potential for transforming social, political, and physical brownfields into healthy and productive living systems. The Studio concentrates on areas within the arts, civics and community, agriculture and environment, disaster relief, and veterans issues. In fiscal year 2016 the Metabolic Studio continued working in Los Angeles and Owens Valley to support free public programming that explores, among other subjects, water, seed, soil-building, remediation, sustainability, and community process. Metabolic Studio continued developing their website at www.metabolicstudio.org in addition to its social media outlets. Metabolic Studio is working towards a relaunch of its website in 2017. The Metabolic Studio is now in its eight year of operating from the VA West Los Angeles Medical Center property (VA-WLA). Here, among many other actions, the Metabolic Studio continued to maintain a therapeutic vegetable garden for the enjoyment and participation of veterans. Participants in therapy programs on the campus and the broader veteran community are invited to learn and participate in organic juicing workshops that promote healthy growing and eating. The Metabolic Studio supports and sponsors the annual Veterans Day Barbeque, held on campus, which provides food and activities to all veterans and their families each November 11th. In the Owens Valley, the Metabolic Studio continued to work to connect the city of Los Angeles with its watershed and the communities that live there. As a component of its consideration of a century of water use, the Studio created the DWP IOU Garden on Main Street in Lone Pine, California. In fiscal year 2016, the IOU Garden continued to produce and distribute free organic soil to the Owens Valley community and provided both a food- growing site for local food banks and a locus for community education and discussion. The IOU Garden taught free weekly public workshops on sustainable growing practices during the summer growing season and hosted regular open community conversations. The Studio continued to produce the IOU Theatre, a summer stock radio play series that featured Owens Valley community members. The IOU Theatre gave live performances at the Double L Bar and local schools in Lone Pine, CA and broadcast those performances online and on the radio. In downtown Los Angeles, the Metabolic Studio continued to plan and design Bending the River Back into the City. With the assistance of over 25 governmental permitting agencies (city, county, state, and federal), this project will consist of an aqueduct/dam diverting water from the Los Angeles River, a storage and treatment center, and a delivery system for distribution and beneficial use of the water at various community locations along the Los Angeles River corridor. The Metabolic Studio aims to raise public consciousness throughout the city regarding the source of its water and to create an awareness to appreciate and conserve this precious and limited resource. During 2016, Metabolic Studio hosted free public community workshops called Reimagine Everything that provided instruction, resources, and tools in various art production techniques such as printmaking, silk-screening, embroidery and other art expressions. These weekly workshops acted as a facilitator for creative expression and community gathering.

Form 990-PF, Part IX-A Line 4: Annenberg Learner (Washington, DC) Annenberg Learner, a program of The Annenberg Foundation, advances excellent teaching in American schools by creating and distributing multimedia educational resources for teachers and students and by communicating best teaching practices to educators, administrators, and the public. These resources and outreach provide current information on learning research and content updates across many disciplines. Annenberg Learner contracts with award-winning multimedia producers who work with academic and professional development experts in each discipline to create the video, print, and web resources. Annenberg Learner distributes these resources in hard copy format (print guides and DVDs), and provides free access to digital formats through its website: www.learner.org. Learner.org is one of the most used websites for teacher professional development. Teachers and other visitors are referred to learner.org by educational websites and blogs including Weebly, Open Culture, Science Spot, All in One Homeschool, Facebook, Google Classroom, and scores of others. Thousands of teachers use the materials for informal continuing education. The most frequently accessed courses and series on learner.org in 2016 were The Habitable Planet: A Systems Approach to Environmental Science; Destinos: Introduction to Spanish; A Biography of America; Discovering Psychology; and Art Through Time: A Global View. Annenberg Learner continued to work with three credit-granting institutions to give teachers across the country the option to acquire graduate credit or continuing education units for Annenberg Learner courses. In 2016, more than 380 teachers registered to earn graduate credit through one of Learners partner institutions that offer credit and another 84 teachers used the materials to gain continuing education units. The University of San Diego offered 9 Learner courses through its Implementation and Planning series. Long-time partner Colorado State University offered 15 titles for continuing education units (CEUs) and 55 titles for graduate credit. PBS Teacherline offered four of its courses as a moderated online professional development experience with optional graduate credit and another 20 as self-paced short courses. The top courses taken by teachers for graduate education credit were: The Habitable Planet; Neuroscience & the Classroom: Making Connections; Americas History in the Making; Teaching Foreign Languages: K-12 Workshop; and The Learning Classroom: Theory into Practice. Additionally, 35 colleges and universities licensed the courses to offer for undergraduate credit, both on campus and at a distance. Among the most frequently licensed courses were American Cinema; Destinos; Against All Odds: Inside Statistics; Art of the Western World; and Power of Place: Geography for the 21st Century. Annenberg Learner updated its highly regarded professional development resource for foreign language teachers in FY 2016 with videos of Arabic language classrooms. The Teaching Arabic Collection, which was co-funded by the Qatar Foundation International (QFI), was developed to help the growing number of Arabic language teachers use best practices as defined by the World Readiness Standards for Learning Languages. Seven Arabic classrooms from elementary through high school grades show student- centered teaching, and an overview video describes the goals of the project. All materials are subtitled in English and Arabic for use by native Arabic speakers. Extending its outreach to teachers, for the third year Annenberg Learner sponsored a summer professional development institute with the Newseum. Using materials from the Newseums newspaper archive collection and online resources from NewseumEd and Learner, participants learned how to incorporate media into their lessons and how to discuss the First Amendment with their students. Annenberg Learner also contributed resources to the Civics Renewal Networks website. The Network is an alliance of 26 organizations working together to raise the visibility of civics education, improve the quality of classroom resources, and strengthen civic life in the United States. Annenberg Learner provided financial support through sponsorships to the Smithsonian Center for Learning and Digital Access and the Council of Chief State School Officers for their annual spring event honoring the teachers of the year from 56 states and territories. Learner was also a major sponsor of StoryCorps second annual Great Thanksgiving Listen to encourage U.S. high school students to interview their elder family members and record the interview through the StoryCorps mobile phone app. More than 21,000 individuals from all 50 states took part in this project over the holiday weekend. Many of these interviews were uploaded to the Library of Congress audio archive to collect and preserve stories from American families. Annenberg Learner continued its outreach to the education community, working with national organizations in materials production and distribution. Staff attended and made presentations at national education conferences including National Science Teachers Association, National Council for the Teachers of Mathematics, American Council for the Teaching of Foreign Languages, and National Council on Social Studies. Social media campaigns continued through Facebook, Twitter, YouTube, Google+, Pinterest, and LinkedIn. The Annenberg Learner blog, LearnerLog, provides teachers with in- depth discussions of content and teaching issues. Journey North, a popular citizen science program for grades 5-12 that engages students in a global study of wildlife migration and seasonal change, reached its 23rd year with Annenberg Learner. Annually, the program involves more than 90,000 students, teachers, and members of the public contributing sightings and other data to the site to share with schools and scientists.
